SIMPLE: ague
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: ague
<hw>a"gue</hw> <pr>(⟦amac⟧"g⟦usl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>agu</ets>, <ets>ague</ets>, OF. <ets>agu</ets>, F. <ets>aigu</ets>,
sharp, OF. fem. <ets>ague</ets>, LL. (febris) <ets>acuta</ets>, a sharp,
acute fever, fr. L. <ets>acutus</ets> sharp. See <er>Acute</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An acute fever.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Brenning <xex>agues</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>P.
Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A fever characterized by paroxysms
of high fever and shaking chills.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>AS</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The cold fit or rigor of malaria or any other
intermittent fever; <as>as, fever and <ex>ague</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>AS</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A chill, or state of shaking, as with cold.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj> <ver>AS</ver>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ague cake</b></col>, <cd>an enlargement of the spleen
produced by ague.</cd> -- <col><b>Ague drop</b></col>, <cd>a solution of
the arsenite of potassa used for ague.</cd> -- <col><b>Ague
fit</b></col>, <cd>a fit of the ague.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> --
<col><b>Ague spell</b></col>, <cd>a spell or charm against ague.</cd>
<au>Gay.</au> -- <col><b>Ague tree</b></col>, <cd>the sassafras, --
sometimes so called from the use of its root formerly, in cases of
ague.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ague</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ague
<hw>A"gue</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Agued</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To strike with an
ague, or with a cold fit.</def> <rj><au>Heywood.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>agueweed</ent>⟦br⟧
